  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight: it characterizes failures statistically and via model internals (neuron coverage) and links failures to specific input transformations and to certain sub-models, but it does not trace failures to underlying root causes such as biased or corrupted training data, spurious features, or detailed feature-level attributions. The analyses show which transformations and which parts of the network are associated with erroneous behavior and demonstrate mitigation via retraining with synthetic data, but they stop short of explaining the learned-model vulnerabilities that produce those failures.",
  "evidence": "pg. 3, (Abstract / Contributions): \"We empirically demonstrate that changes in neuron coverage are statistically correlated with changes in the actions of self-driving cars (e.g., steering angle).\"; pg. 305, Section 3.1 (Systematic Testing with Neuron Coverage): \"Neuron coverage ... is defined as the ratio of unique neurons that get activated for given input(s) and the total number of neurons in a DNN\"; pg. 308, Section 5 (RQ1 Result): \"Result 1: Neuron coverage is correlated with input-output diversity and can be used to systematic test generation.\"; pg. 309, Section 5 (RQ2 Result): \"Result 2: Different image transformations tend to activate different sets of neurons.\"; pg. 311, Section 5 (RQ4 / reporting): \"Interestingly, some models are more prone to erroneous behaviors for some transformations than others.\" (Table 8 and discussion show per-transformation, per-model failure counts); pg. 311, Section 5 (RQ5 Result): \"Result 5: Accuracy of a DNN can be improved up to 46% by retraining the DNN with synthetic data generated by DeepTest.\".  Nowhere in the paper do the authors perform root-cause analyses that link failures to specific training-data biases, spurious features, or detailed feature-attribution analyses of the learned model (i.e., they characterize where failures occur but do not explain why the model learned the vulnerable behavior)."
